# Tailwind v4: CSS Variable Ambiguity

In Tailwind v4, `text-[var(--something)]` is ambiguous — the framework cannot determine if a CSS variable is a **color** or a **font-size**, so it defaults to `color`. This causes silent rendering bugs when you intend to set font-size.

## Rule

Never use `text-[var(--text-*)]` for font-size. Use the theme utility instead.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — Tailwind treats both as color, font-size never applies
className="text-[var(--text-xs)] text-[var(--color-danger)]"

// ✅ GOOD — use theme utility for font-size, arbitrary value for color
className="text-xs text-[var(--color-danger)]"
```

## Why

Theme values defined in `@theme` (e.g., `--text-xs: 11px`) automatically generate utilities (`text-xs`). Using `text-[var(--text-xs)]` bypasses theme lookup and creates an arbitrary value that Tailwind defaults to `color: var(--text-xs)` — which is invalid CSS.

## Quick Reference

| Intent | Correct | Wrong |
|--------|---------|-------|
| Font size 11px | `text-xs` | `text-[var(--text-xs)]` |
| Font size 13px | `text-sm` | `text-[var(--text-sm)]` |
| Font size 14px | `text-base` | `text-[var(--text-base)]` |
| Font size 16px | `text-lg` | `text-[var(--text-lg)]` |
| Text color | `text-[var(--color-text-primary)]` | (this is fine) |

If you must use an arbitrary CSS variable for font-size, use the data type hint: `text-[length:var(--my-size)]`.
